Final Assignment:¶

The aim of this project is to investigate the influence of Cholesterol and glucose on BMI.¶

The data is collected from the Lifeline dataset including; "continious" and "complete". The "continious" data set referes to the case in which a person has been participated in both data collection times. While, the "complete" data set referes to the case in which a person has participated in one or both data collection times. For more information please read the "Toolkit - Aletta Year Challenge 2022" pdf file.

It should be noted that the "continious" data sets are required since, the goal was to understand a relationship between changes in glucose or cholesterol, and BMI variations.

def seperate_columns(df):

    df = df.columns.to_frame().T.append(df, ignore_index=True) #convert header to row
    df.columns = range(len(df.columns)) #number the column
    df = df[0].str.split('\t', expand=True) #split columns
    df.columns = df.iloc[0] # consider the first row as header
    df = df[1:] #eliminate first row which was the copy of header
    
    return df

Which data is required:¶

ZIPCODE: Postal code 4 Baseline visit 1

GENDER: Gender (1=male, 2=female)

GENDER_MALE: Male participants in percentage

GENDER_FEMALE: Female participants in percentage

BMI_T1:Body Mass Index (kg/M^2) at baseline as mean (T1)

BMI_T2:Body Mass Index (kg/M^2) at baseline as mean (T2)

CHO_T1:Cholesterol (mmol/L) assessed on samples from baseline as mean (T1)

CHO_T2:Cholesterol (mmol/L) assessed on samples from second assessment second visit as mean (T2)

GLU_T1:Glucose (mmol/L) assessed on samples from baseline as mean (T1)

GLU_T2:Glucose (mmol/L) assessed on samples from second assessment secondvisit as mean (T2)

def correlation_heatmap(df= heatmap1_df):
    
    # Generate a custom diverging colormap
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)
    
    # calculate correlation
    correlation = df.corr()
    
    # plot heatmap by seaborn gallery
    plt.title('Percentage of Correlation', fontsize=18)
    sns.heatmap(correlation, annot = True, cmap=cmap, vmin=0, vmax=1)
    plt.show()
    
correlation_heatmap(df= overall_heatmap)
correlation_heatmap(df= heatmap1_df)
correlation_heatmap(df= heatmap2_df)

Part 7: Regression Model:¶

To obtain an appropriate regression model, the Calibration class (written by M.Emile F.Apol) has been used. The summary of mentioned calibration class is called, and accordingly a table is generated which consists of information about Delta values based on defferent models.

A Delta value is calculated with the AIC method (Akaike Information Criterion method). To be noted that based on the AIC method, the best model is the lowest delta value.

Note:¶

delta_BMI1, delta_CHO1, delta_GLU1 = When gendar is seperated by percentage

delta_BMI2, delta_CHO2, delta_GLU2 = When gendar is seperated by code: 1=male, 2=female

Regression model for the relation between Cholesterol and BMI¶

Part 8: Conclusion:¶

In this research, the relationship between glucose, cholesterol, and BMI has been investigated. The datasets is used from the lifeline, and two datasets based on "ZIPCODE" are merged. To evaluate the influence of glucose and cholesterole variations on BMI changes, delta_BMI, delta_CHO, and delta_GLU are calculated. Data are seperated into two categories such as either gender by percentage, or gender by codes (e.g, 1= male and 2= female).Therefor, there have been two delta values available for the three required parameteres.

The correlation and heatmap used to understand the relationship between parameteres. As heatmaps show, when data is collected by gender percentage, cholesterol has more effect on BMI than Glucose. In contrast, in the condition of data collection by gender codes(male = 1, female = 2), it was obviously shown that the influence of glucose on BMI was more.

After that, the Normality of BMI was tested by Q_Q_plot and Q_Q_hist modules which indicated BMI data was normal.

In order to find the best regression model, the Calibration class(written by M.Emile F. Apol) is called from the "Summary_functions_and_code_clean_v11" module. Using the "summary" of the calibration class, a table is obtained which illustrates an appropriate regression model based on the 'delta' value. Finally, thementioned regression model and the real data are plotted.

In conclusion, this study illustrates that the value of glucose and cholesterol has a slight influence on the BMI value, and the best regression models has been generated.
